segments.text: Were there any other characters like him?
Not like Dr. Wharton.
There were no other characters like Dr. Wharton.
He was something else.
You couldn't help but admire the man.
He was a good- In what way?
Because of his memory?
Because of his knowledge?
He had the knowledge, yes.
He knew.
He was too busy otherwise with his personal affairs to bother with you.
Unless you ask him a specific question.
He was there with you.
What did the administration think of his personal affairs?
They didn't care for that so much, did they, back in the 1930s?
His first wife died.
He made a statement.
And that statement got out to the president.
It got back to him.
Quickly.
Yeah, real quickly.
So Dr. Wharton came in.
What was his statement?
Well, this was her death he talked about.
This was something that he had devoutly wished for.
or something like that.
Anyhow, that's what I heard.
He didn't tell me.
But anyway, he had his, I think it was a Form 501 in those days that they issued when they fired you.
When he came in that morning, that thing was on his desk.
It was on a Saturday morning.
as I recall, and I was his graduate assistant that year.
This was in 35, wasn't it?
So I didn't see him for a while.
And finally, Dr. Marsdell got a hold of me, said, we don't have any grades for those seniors.
And the grades are supposed to be in today.
Will you try to find Dr. Wharton, get him to grade those papers?
turn in those grades before 5 o'clock.
So these seniors can, these students can, well, it wasn't graduation anyway.
They had to have the grades in by 5.
That was the deadline anyway.
I found Dr. Wharton.
He was in the old baron's tavern in Bryan drinking beer.
So he said, John,
I am no longer on the faculty at A&M, and if Dr. Marsteller wants those papers graded, he can grade them himself.
I said, I don't care what he does with them.
Well, I told Dr. Marsteller, Dr. Wharton is not going to grade the papers.
He said, well, you get up there and grade those papers and turn in the grade for them.
Well, I went up to the lab, and his office was in the laboratory.
in one corner of the lab.
So I graded the papers and got their grades in.
I graded them as best I could.
Old Dr. Wharton told me that morning, he said, John, if you ever go to work for Texas A&M, I'm going to cut your GD throat.
Really?
Ruth heard it.
She was sitting in the car.
The old brother.
What happened to them and them?
Hm?
What happened to Wharton and them?
He went to San Antonio and became chief of meat inspection for the city of San Antonio.
And then he had eight wives after that?
Well, he had gone through the second wife here.
I thought you said the first one died.
Well, his first one died.
And that's when he got fired for making this statement?
Well, he had married to another one before this first one died.
Oh, really?
See, they were divorced.
Well, he and the second one didn't get along any better than he and the first one.
So I was in lab one morning, and this second wife came in.
She had on a great big picture hat, you know, one of those wide-brimmed things.
She had it pulled down over one of her eyes, and she was looking for Dr. Horton.
Dr. Wharton, not here.
She said, well, I am going to have to leave him.
I cannot live with him.
Well, by that time, she had raised that hat up enough I could see that big black eye.
Oh, really?
I found out then that she had been down at old Ed Hardlick's.
That was Uncle Ed's place.
You've heard about that.
I think it's...
It's Fish Richards now down in there.
That's where the students always hung out and drank their beers on.
Well, anyway, the night before, Dr. Wharton had been to a meeting of the junior chapter of the American Binaural Medical Association.
He was sponsor.
It was in the old amphitheater at Francis Hall.
Someone came in and said something to him.
Doc just stayed in the group until the meeting was over, and then he left.
He stopped by Ed Hardlicker's.
When he went in, his wife was sitting at a table.
And he just walked right on by her and down to the bar, got a beer.
Well, before he finished that bottle of beer,
Someone came and tapped him on the shoulder and said, Doc, your wife just fell out of the chair.
She's on the floor back there, drunk.
So Doc said, well, pick her up.
You saw her first.
Well, this old boy went back, picked her up, and took her out and put her in Doc's car in the front seat.
Doc went ahead and finished his beer.
I don't know whether he had another one or two or what.
But anyway, when he went out, she was lying there in the front seat, you know, head back on the back of the seat.
She was out.
But when Doc got in the car, his wife awakened.
Well, she knew that he kept a pistol in the pocket, in the car pocket, on the dash pocket.
So she tried to get it.
And when she tried it, he hit her in her eye.
That's when he hit her in that left eye.
Knocked her loose from it.
And that's where the big black eye came from.
So anyhow, he was canned.
He was fired.
As his assistant, were you sorry to see him go?
Well, yes, I liked old Doc.
He and I got along all right.
I didn't take anything off of him.
I didn't give him anything to take either.
Because I was just a graduate assistant, and I did what I was told.
And did the best I could with the students.
I tried to give them something when they came to class.
But that's the reason.
I had no pathology.
to amount to anything.
That's the reason that Ruth and I went to Ann Arbor to University of Michigan Medical School and we took every course they had, graduate and undergraduate, in pathology.
So I figured that I would go on teaching pathology.
And I could tell you that we had nothing, we had no material for

microscopic work whatsoever all that had been thrown out so i began in in the from 1936 to 1941 when i went into anatomy i had prepared over 400 class sets of various diseases i had no technician i had to do all that i was the only one in pathology
I did all of the post-mortem work for the College of Veterinary Medicine.
I preserved all the gross specimens.
I made I don't know how many museum jars that we fixed up on, so Ruth would go out with me, that we would fix up on Sundays, prepare these specimens for class work.
And sectioning tissue.
Well, you gave all the lectures.
You graded all the papers.
You did all the, you were the only one.
And one semester in there, the pathology department was combined with bacteriology.
It was pathology and bacteriology.
Then it placed under Dr. Dunn, who later became dean.
There was one semester, Dr. Dunn was sick.
He was out the entire semester.
This was about 38, 39, 38, 39, somewhere in there.
Well, we got old Dr. Van Valkenburg to come down and handle the immunology.
And I had all of the path and all of the bacteriology.
Well, now, if you can imagine,
I section tissue, prepare material for classwork and pathology, laboratory work and pathology.
I am doing all the post-mortem work.
I have to keep, I don't know how many different cultures of bacteria we had, but you have to transfer and keep everything going.
You have to make up all the special medias and so on for detection of carbohydrates and so on, gas fermentation and what have you, blood media and what have you.
You have to do all that yourself.
That was one semester.
Dr. Dunn, I didn't see him from the beginning of the semester to the last of the semester.
I was handling everything in bacteriology and pathology.
except immunology.
Dr. Van Valkenburg took it.
I got a thank you.
And that was $1,800 on a nine-month basis.
And people bellyache now about having to work so much.
I have one last question about Dr. Wharton.
It appears that to you, is it true that he was then fired because of his private life?
Well, I think more private life than anything else.
Not because of his professional life?
No, I don't think so.
What did the staff, what did your colleagues and yourself think about the fact that he was fired because of his private life and not because of his professional life?
I don't know what they thought about him.
I really don't.
They probably had the same feeling that I had, that he deserved it.
I wouldn't have wanted him on the staff the way things were.
In fact, it may have been a repeat later on.
I don't know.
I'm not going to send anybody.
But anyway.
What do you mean a repeat?
No, I had to fire a person.
Oh, yeah?
In fact, I fired two.
In the 50s?
No, no.
This was way later in anatomy.
Well, there was one.
I inherited one when I went in the department.
He admitted that he was a misfit.
He would like to have gone on in human medicine, and it was an embarrassment to him that he was in veterinary medicine.
I said, well, if that's the way you feel about it, then you don't deserve to be in here with veterinary students.
If you don't think that veterinary medicine is the only profession in the world, you don't deserve to be in here teaching.
I don't want you.
And so I went on over to Dr. Marsteller's office and told him to fill out a form 501 for him.
Well, this old boy went to Dr. Marsteller that same morning, well, within the hour.
And Dr. Marsteller said, unless you can patch it up with Dr. Melliff, why, I'm going to have to let you go.
Because he's already been by here.
I'll fill out this form to fire you.
This fella came up and talked to me.
I said, well, I'll try you the remainder of the semester.
And unless you change your mind about veterinary medicine by September, you better be in another position somewhere else.
I'll give you this summer.
to look around.
You'll be on salary this summer, but you can look around and find you another place.
Well, that summer, he decided he'd go on back to medical.
He'd go to medical school, and he did.
He went to St. Louis University School of Medicine.
What he did, he stayed two years and quit, and still he's practicing veterinary medicine to this day.
He is.
Yeah.
He doesn't like human medicine either.
He thought that was it.
What about the other one, the other person?
Well, the other one is still living.
And I hope he's doing well.
But he just had too many things to do with the opposite sex.
And he was married and a family and so on.
So we had a trial.

and this led to the establishment of dismissal procedures following the aup's recommendations i'm sure about when was this this was in the late 60s it took three years to set it up but we had a trial with jury lawyers and everything he had lawyers and the nm had lawyers but i hope that now with their committee on grievances or whatever it is
There is a faculty committed to look into a dismissal of a person.
And it has to be on firm ground.
You can't just fire a man because you don't like him.
That's the way it was before this was set up.
And I guess it's a good thing that it was set up.
But in those days, before we ever had it, I didn't know
any mistreatment of an individual if he did his work.
I don't think Wharton would have ever been fired if he hadn't just, well, it was too glaring.
It was too obvious of what he was doing.
He made no big secret of it.
But he never did bring anything on the campus.
All of his dirty work, I would say,
was done off the campus.
But his name attached to A&M wasn't good for A&M.
That was it.
In the war and until 1969, you were head of the Department of Vet and Anatomy.
Yeah.
It was the same thing when I went into Veterinary Anatomy.
We had nothing.
Okay, I'd like to talk about those changes.
So, Dr. Mundink was head of the department, left, went with Latterly Laboratories.
Dr. Rubin had come here two years before with Dr. Mundink.
So, Rubin and I were, well, Dr. Lange, L-A-N-G-E, called it Lange.
Dr. Lange
was here then too, Dr. Longy and Dr. Rubin.
And Dr. Longy had the idea, so he told me that he should have been made head of department instead of me.
In fact, they look around and they get this younger person.
So he told me that this younger person, this snip, to take the headship when he had been in the department for two years.
He actually should have been made head of department.
Well, that was the beginning.
Actually, I was older than Lang, as I call him, Lang, instead of Longy.
I was older than he was, but he didn't know it.
And I had had more education than Dr. Lang.
In fact, I had two more degrees at that time than Dr. Lang had.
So, well, he's the one who I had to let go.
And our differences began right about that time.
When I went into the department, he was so unhappy because he wasn't made head of department.
And that's what he told me.
So I called him one day down.
I called up one day down there.
I don't know.
I had a question, something I wanted to ask you if it was.
down there, or had I overlooked it in Francis Hall.
We had the little two-story building, which is in civil engineering now.
It was the anatomy lab.
He was down there, and I was up on the hill, as we called it, at Francis Hall.
No, he didn't know where it was, and so on, and so on.
He gave me a piece of his mind then.
for calling him up.
He was in class, didn't want to be disturbed.
I said, where are you?
So that's when I went down to see him.
I said, you just stay right there till I get there, because we're going to have some words.
I went down there, and he was in class.
He kept on lecturing.
I just stood in the door, watched him a while.
He didn't even look my way.
He knew I was there.
That's when I went on over to Dr. Marsteller and told him to fill out the 501 for him.
I wasn't going to put up with him.
But he came and talked to me, as I said.
And we patched it up.
He stayed on until the end of the summer.
Then went back to medical school.
Went to medical school.
There must have been a great change in curriculum while you were department head.
Well, we added courses.
I think the big change was in the improvement of teaching.
OK. Let's talk about that.
Why did it improve?
Well, it improved because we were endeavoring to build up a department.
from nothing.
And we had it.
There was no way to go but up.
And unless you went up, you might as well quit.
It was just that bad.
So we began improving our teaching methods.
We began to get materials that
would allow us to present our subject to the students in a much better way.
Projectors and such as that and microscopes.
Lord, we needed everything.
And laboratory tables and chairs and you name it, we needed it.
Because we didn't have anything.
We were down to what we could rake and scrape out of a basement.
And that was about it.
Microscopes, the big thing at first, we had no trouble getting animals for gross dissection.
In fact, I don't believe we ever had any trouble.
Dr. Francis didn't seem to have trouble getting live material for gross dissection.
embalming, preparation specimen, wet specimen material.
He had no trouble.
But it was in the microscopic part.
Embryology, we had nothing.
And we had to order most of our embryology material because it was an impossibility for me, as head of department and technician too, to make

histology material and embryology material, too, because making embryology slide serial sections is much harder work than just cutting sections for histology, where you just put one section on the slide.
If you have to have a 24-hour chick serial sections all on one slide, that's much more difficult.
We ordered most of the embryology material.
We bought a 600 egg incubator.
We would start out hatching with eggs and break eggs every day and watch the development.
This was for embryology.
And then when the chicks hatched out, we usually have several hundred chicks.
We would sex them.
I learned to sex chicks, baby chicks, one day old.
We had lots of fun that way.
And then usually, just as an aside, we would separate the cocks from the hens, from the pullets.
And one boy would take all the cocks, and another one would take the hens, and we'd raise them all up to frying size and check, see how good we were in sexing.
See how many hens we had over there
with the roosters.
Well, when they got up to be frying sides, we always had a big barbecue.
The class was out here, out that old patio out there.
Really?
Right out there?
Yeah, right out there.
And so they usually bring a keg of beer.
I wouldn't have anything to do with it, but they'd have a keg of beer out there somewhere.
We'd have a big chicken barbecue.
Great.
Big deal, yeah.
Lots of fun.
Of course, these were older students.
But it paid off.
But I don't know.
Altogether, in histology in those years, when I had no technician, I don't know how many class sets I prepared.
In pathology, I had over 400 sets when I left there.
And I don't suppose there's a veterinary college in this country that could equal our collection in histology and embryology and neuroanatomy now.
And I did most of the sectioning.
I had help from 1955 on.
But the help that I got had to be taught.
And so there was a period of years when actually,
I was still doing most of the technical help because I was teaching the person I had hired.
You couldn't hire anybody else.
You didn't have money enough to hire a graduate technician.
So as a consequence, we found a person who was willing to work, a good worker.
She was working over there at Black's Pharmacy on Old Jones Pharmacy now, or whatever.
I taught her, and she got to be, I guess, she was about the best tissue technician on the campus.
She's retired now from A&M, but she was with me from then on until I retired in 71.
A good technician, and I don't have any others she taught.
For years, you were chairman of the Student Selections Committee.
Yes.
That was one of your important committee jobs.
Could you describe this election process?
And did it change over the years?
I couldn't tell you whether it has changed very much or not now because I haven't kept up with it.
But in those days, we tried to evaluate the student as best we could.
We looked at everything that we had on that student.
His transcript was the big thing, what he had done in his college work.
This was in the 1940s and 1950s?
Well, this was in the 50s.
Back in the 40s, Dr. Dunn was chairman of the committee.
And he had a way of evaluating, too.
They had a sort of a score method, so many points if he had
a year on the farm, and so many points if he belonged to the 4-H group, and so on and so on.
And so you totaled up your score to evaluate the students.
But we went more on the transcript, on his college record, what he had to show us.
There's so much that can be learned from a transcript, but just besides grades.
whether the student stayed with what he started out.
In my own instance, I began with EE, and I changed to biology, and then I changed to veterinary medicine.
Well, I don't know whether I would have thought very much of that in evaluating me or not.
Because I just hadn't made up my mind.
I was a little bit too changeable.
And I dropped some courses and so on.
Well, that didn't speak well for a student in his evaluation.
If he started out in veterinary medicine, then he had his mind made up.
If he started out in pre-vet, he had his mind made up back yonder that veterinary medicine was actually what he wanted.
You had to find out something about motivation, whether he really wanted it and how long he had wanted it and so on.
How did you find out about that?
Didn't you have interviews?
Oh, yes.
You had interviews.
What were the important questions during the interviews?
The important questions on his coursework and on his life up to the time.
And, of course, we had letters from various persons, letters of recommendation.
But those things couldn't always be taken.
face value.
Perhaps you know yourself, if you've ever written a letter of recommendation, you've tried to avoid saying anything that might be derogatory.
Well, another thing about our selection from the time that Al Price became dean, we had to
have everything so that whatever we decided about a student would stand up in court.
Absolutely.
You didn't just...
When was this?
When did this come about?
Well, this was from the time that Al Price became dean only.
Why?
Why did they change the policy?
You can be hailed into court now
any student can take you into court anytime he wants to the way things are going now you see that every day lawsuits so unless you have it in black and white
You just better not draw it off the top of your head.
And just because you think something is so, you better know it for sure.
So the graves were the big things that you had to go on.
This was all in black and white.
This is a record.
And it's a record that you can take into court.
Do you remember any law cases against the Selections Committee?
No, I don't recall any.
I think we've been threatened.
But I know I never had to appear.
You know, during the, over the years, from the mid-30s to the mid-60s, the requirements and the number of...
